<p><b>Statistics</b> (from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_=
language" title=3D"German language">German</a>: <i><span lang=3D"de"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Statistik#German" class=3D"extiw" title=
=3D"wikt:Statistik">Statistik</a></span></i>, <abbr title=3D"originally">or=
ig.</abbr> "description of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/State=
_(polity)" title=3D"State (polity)">state</a>, a country"<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-:1_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stat=
istics#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) is the discipline that concerns the coll=
ection, organization, analysis, interpretation, and presentation of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">data</a>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-def_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Statistics#cite_note-def-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In applying statistics to a scie=
ntific, industrial, or social problem, it is conventional to begin with a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"St=
atistical population">statistical population</a> or a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model" title=3D"Statistical model">statisti=
cal model</a> to be studied. Populations can be diverse groups of people or=
 objects such as "all people living in a country" or "every atom composing =
a crystal". Statistics deals with every aspect of data, including the plann=
ing of data collection in terms of the design of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Statistical_survey" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistic=
al survey">surveys</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experim=
ental_design" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Experimental design">experimen=
ts</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dodge_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Dodge-3"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Census" title=3D"Censu=
s">census</a> data (comprising every member of the target population) canno=
t be collected, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistician" titl=
e=3D"Statistician">statisticians</a> collect data by developing specific ex=
periment designs and survey <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample=
_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample (statistics)">samples<=
/a>. Representative sampling assures that inferences and conclusions can re=
asonably extend from the sample to the population as a whole. An <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_study" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Experimental study">experimental study</a> involves taking measureme=
nts of the system under study, manipulating the system, and then taking add=
itional measurements using the same procedure to determine if the manipulat=
ion has modified the values of the measurements. In contrast, an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observational_study" title=3D"Observational =
study">observational study</a> does not involve experimental manipulation.
</p><p>Two main statistical methods are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Data_analysis" title=3D"Data analysis">data analysis</a>: <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statistics" title=3D"Desc=
riptive statistics">descriptive statistics</a>, which summarize data from a=
 sample using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Index_(statistics)" =
title=3D"Index (statistics)">indexes</a> such as the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mean</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard=
 deviation</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_in=
ference" title=3D"Statistical inference">inferential statistics</a>, which =
draw conclusions from data that are subject to random variation (e.g., obse=
rvational errors, sampling variation).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LundResearchLtd_4=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics=
#cite_note-LundResearchLtd-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Descriptive statistics are most of=
ten concerned with two sets of properties of a <i>distribution</i> (sample =
or population): <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_tendenc=
y" title=3D"Central tendency">central tendency</a></i> (or <i>location</i>)=
 seeks to characterize the distribution's central or typical value, while <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_dispersion" title=3D=
"Statistical dispersion">dispersion</a></i> (or <i>variability</i>) charact=
erizes the extent to which members of the distribution depart from its cent=
er and each other. Inferences made using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematical_statistics" title=3D"Mathematical statistics">mathemati=
cal statistics</a> employ the framework of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theor=
y</a>, which deals with the analysis of random phenomena.
</p><p>A standard statistical procedure involves the collection of data lea=
ding to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_t=
esting" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">test=
 of the relationship</a> between two statistical data sets, or a data set a=
nd synthetic data drawn from an idealized model. A hypothesis is proposed f=
or the statistical relationship between the two data sets, an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternative_hypothesis" title=3D"Alternative hy=
pothesis">alternative</a> to an idealized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> of n=
o relationship between two data sets. Rejecting or disproving the null hypo=
thesis is done using statistical tests that quantify the sense in which the=
 null can be proven false, given the data that are used in the test. Workin=
g from a null hypothesis, two basic forms of error are recognized: <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Type I error">Type I errors</a> (null hypothesis is rejected when it is=
 in fact true, giving a "false positive") and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Type_II_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type II error">Ty=
pe II errors</a> (null hypothesis fails to be rejected when it is in fact f=
alse, giving a "false negative"). Multiple problems have come to be associa=
ted with this framework, ranging from obtaining a sufficient sample size to=
 specifying an adequate null hypothesis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LundResearchLtd=
_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statisti=
cs#cite_note-LundResearchLtd-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Statistical measurement processes are also prone to error in regards=
 to the data that they generate. Many of these errors are classified as ran=
dom (noise) or systematic (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias_(s=
tatistics)" title=3D"Bias (statistics)">bias</a>), but other types of error=
s (e.g., blunder, such as when an analyst reports incorrect units) can also=
 occur. The presence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Missing_da=
ta" title=3D"Missing data">missing data</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Censoring_(statistics)" title=3D"Censoring (statistics)">censo=
ring</a> may result in biased estimates and specific techniques have been d=
eveloped to address these problems.
</p>
