<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Introduction">Introduction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Introduction"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outline_of_statistic=
s" title=3D"Outline of statistics">Outline of statistics</a></div>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>"Statistics is both the science of u=
ncertainty and the technology of extracting information from data." - featu=
red in the International Encyclopedia of Statistical Science.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Hand20102_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Hand20102-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote><p>Stat=
istics is the discipline that deals with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">data</a>, facts and figures with which meaningf=
ul information is inferred. Data may represent a numerical value, in form o=
f quantitative data, or a label, as with qualitative data. Data may be coll=
ected, presented and summarised, in one of two methods called descriptive s=
tatistics. Two elementary summaries of data, singularly called a statistic,=
 are the mean and dispersion. Whereas inferential statistics interprets dat=
a from a population sample to induce statements and predictions about a pop=
ulation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:12_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-:12-6"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-:2_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistics#cite_note-:2-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hand20102_5-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_n=
ote-Hand20102-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Statistics is regarded as a body of science<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#=
cite_note-:3-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> or a branch of mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#c=
ite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> It is based on probability, a branch of mathematics =
that studies random events. Statistics is considered the science of uncerta=
inty. This arises from the ways to cope with measurement and sampling error=
 as well as dealing with uncertanties in modelling. Although probability an=
d statistics were once paired together as a single subject, they are concep=
tually distinct from one another. The former is based on deducing answers t=
o specific situations from a general theory of probability, meanwhile stati=
stics induces statements about a population based on a data set. Statistics=
 serves to bridge the gap between probability and applied mathematical fiel=
ds.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hand20=
102_5-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati=
stics#cite_note-Hand20102-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-11"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Some consider statistics to be a distinct <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_sciences" title=3D"Mathematical sciences">mathe=
matical science</a> rather than a branch of mathematics. While many scienti=
fic investigations make use of data, statistics is generally concerned with=
 the use of data in the context of uncertainty and decision-making in the f=
ace of uncertainty.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistics#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Statistics is indexed at 62, a subclas=
s of probability theory and stochastic processes, in the Mathematics Subjec=
t Classification.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Mathematica=
l statistics is covered in the range 276-280 of subclass QA (science &gt; m=
athematics) in the Library of Congress Classification.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#=
cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The word statistics ultimately comes from the Latin word Status, mea=
ning "situation" or "condition" in society, which in late Latin adopted the=
 meaning "state". Derived from this, political scientist Gottfried Achenwal=
l, coined the German word statistik (a summary of how things stand). In 177=
0, the term entered the English language through German and referred to the=
 study of political arrangements. The term gained its modern meaning in the=
 1790s in John Sinclair's works.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-16"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In modern German, the ter=
m statistik is synonymous with mathematical statistics. The term statistic,=
 in singular form, is used to describe a function that returns its value of=
 the same name.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Statistical_data">Statistic=
al data</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStat=
istics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Statistica=
l data"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Data_collection">Data colle=
ction</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatis=
tics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Data collect=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Sampling">Sampling</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Sampling"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When full census data cannot be collected, statisticians collect sample =
data by developing specific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design=
_of_experiments" title=3D"Design of experiments">experiment designs</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Survey_sampling" title=3D"Survey =
sampling">survey samples</a>. Statistics itself also provides tools for pre=
diction and forecasting through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St=
atistical_model" title=3D"Statistical model">statistical models</a>.
</p><p>To use a sample as a guide to an entire population, it is important =
that it truly represents the overall population. Representative <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Sampling (sta=
tistics)">sampling</a> assures that inferences and conclusions can safely e=
xtend from the sample to the population as a whole. A major problem lies in=
 determining the extent that the sample chosen is actually representative. =
Statistics offers methods to estimate and correct for any bias within the s=
ample and data collection procedures. There are also methods of experimenta=
l design that can lessen these issues at the outset of a study, strengtheni=
ng its capability to discern truths about the population.
</p><p>Sampling theory is part of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematical discipline</a> of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probabilit=
y theory">probability theory</a>. Probability is used in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_theory" title=3D"Statistical theory">mat=
hematical statistics</a> to study the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Sampling_distribution" title=3D"Sampling distribution">sampling distrib=
utions</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_statistic" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample statistic">sample statistics</a> and, m=
ore generally, the properties of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tatistical_decision_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical deci=
sion theory">statistical procedures</a>. The use of any statistical method =
is valid when the system or population under consideration satisfies the as=
sumptions of the method. The difference in point of view between classic pr=
obability theory and sampling theory is, roughly, that probability theory s=
tarts from the given parameters of a total population to <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deductive_reasoning" title=3D"Deductive reasoning">d=
educe</a> probabilities that pertain to samples. Statistical inference, how=
ever, moves in the opposite direction=E2=80=94<a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Inductive_reasoning" title=3D"Inductive reasoning">inductively =
inferring</a> from samples to the parameters of a larger or total populatio=
n.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Experimental_and_observatio=
nal_studies">Experimental and observational studies</h4><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Experimental and observational studies"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>A common goal for a statistical research project is to investigate <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causality" title=3D"Causality">causalit=
y</a>, and in particular to draw a conclusion on the effect of changes in t=
he values of predictors or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depende=
nt_and_independent_variables" title=3D"Dependent and independent variables"=
>independent variables on dependent variables</a>. There are two major type=
s of causal statistical studies: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
xperiment" title=3D"Experiment">experimental studies</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observational_study" title=3D"Observational stud=
y">observational studies</a>. In both types of studies, the effect of diffe=
rences of an independent variable (or variables) on the behavior of the dep=
endent variable are observed. The difference between the two types lies in =
how the study is actually conducted. Each can be very effective. An experim=
ental study involves taking measurements of the system under study, manipul=
ating the system, and then taking additional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Level_of_measurement" title=3D"Level of measurement">measurement=
s with different levels</a> using the same procedure to determine if the ma=
nipulation has modified the values of the measurements. In contrast, an obs=
ervational study does not involve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Scientific_control" title=3D"Scientific control">experimental manipulation<=
/a>. Instead, data are gathered and correlations between predictors and res=
ponse are investigated. While the tools of data analysis work best on data =
from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomized_controlled_trial" =
title=3D"Randomized controlled trial">randomized studies</a>, they are also=
 applied to other kinds of data=E2=80=94like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Natural_experiment" title=3D"Natural experiment">natural experim=
ents</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observational_study" =
title=3D"Observational study">observational studies</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics=
#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>=E2=80=94for which a statistician would use a mod=
ified, more structured estimation method (e.g., <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Difference_in_differences" title=3D"Difference in differences=
">difference in differences estimation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Instrumental_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Instrume=
ntal variable">instrumental variables</a>, among many others) that produce =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistent_estimator" title=3D"Con=
sistent estimator">consistent estimators</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Experiments">Experiments</h=
5><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Experiments"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The basic steps of a statistical experiment are:
</p>
<ol><li>Planning the research, including finding the number of replicates o=
f the study, using the following information:  preliminary estimates regard=
ing the size of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_treatment_=
effect" title=3D"Average treatment effect">treatment effects</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternative_hypothesis" title=3D"Alternat=
ive hypothesis">alternative hypotheses</a>, and the estimated <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Experimental error">experimental variability</a>. Consideration of the =
selection of experimental subjects and the ethics of research is necessary.=
 Statisticians recommend that experiments compare (at least) one new treatm=
ent with a standard treatment or control, to allow an unbiased estimate of =
the difference in treatment effects.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_of_experiments" title=
=3D"Design of experiments">Design of experiments</a>, using <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blocking_(statistics)" title=3D"Blocking (statist=
ics)">blocking</a> to reduce the influence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Confounding_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confoundin=
g variable">confounding variables</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Randomized_assignment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Randomized a=
ssignment">randomized assignment</a> of treatments to subjects to allow <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias_of_an_estimator" title=3D"Bias o=
f an estimator">unbiased estimates</a> of treatment effects and experimenta=
l error. At this stage, the experimenters and statisticians write the <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protocol_(natural_sciences)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Protocol (natural sciences)">experimental protoco=
l</a></i> that will guide the performance of the experiment and which speci=
fies the<i> primary analysis</i> of the experimental data.</li>
<li>Performing the experiment following the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Protocol_(natural_sciences)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Proto=
col (natural sciences)">experimental protocol</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance" title=3D"Analysis of variance">an=
alyzing the data</a> following the experimental protocol.</li>
<li>Further examining the data set in secondary analyses, to suggest new hy=
potheses for future study.</li>
<li>Documenting and presenting the results of the study.</li></ol>
<p>Experiments on human behavior have special concerns. The famous <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawthorne_study" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Hawthorne study">Hawthorne study</a> examined changes to the working=
 environment at the Hawthorne plant of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Western_Electric_Company" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Western E=
lectric Company">Western Electric Company</a>. The researchers were interes=
ted in determining whether increased illumination would increase the produc=
tivity of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assembly_line" title=
=3D"Assembly line">assembly line</a> workers. The researchers first measure=
d the productivity in the plant, then modified the illumination in an area =
of the plant and checked if the changes in illumination affected productivi=
ty. It turned out that productivity indeed improved (under the experimental=
 conditions). However, the study is heavily criticized today for errors in =
experimental procedures, specifically for the lack of a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_group" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Control=
 group">control group</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doub=
le-blind" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Double-blind">blindness</a>. The <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawthorne_effect" title=3D"Hawthorn=
e effect">Hawthorne effect</a> refers to finding that an outcome (in this c=
ase, worker productivity) changed due to observation itself. Those in the H=
awthorne study became more productive not because the lighting was changed =
but because they were being observed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pmid17608932_20-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#ci=
te_note-pmid17608932-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Observational_study">Observ=
ational study</h5><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Obs=
ervational study"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>An example of an observational study is one that explores the associatio=
n between smoking and lung cancer. This type of study typically uses a surv=
ey to collect observations about the area of interest and then performs sta=
tistical analysis. In this case, the researchers would collect observations=
 of both smokers and non-smokers, perhaps through a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cohort_study" title=3D"Cohort study">cohort study</a>, an=
d then look for the number of cases of lung cancer in each group.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistics#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Case-control_study" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Case-control study"=
>case-control study</a> is another type of observational study in which peo=
ple with and without the outcome of interest (e.g. lung cancer) are invited=
 to participate and their exposure histories are collected.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Types_of_data">Types of dat=
a</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Types of data"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_data_ty=
pe" title=3D"Statistical data type">Statistical data type</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levels_of_measurement" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Levels of measurement">Levels of measurement</a></div>
<p>Various attempts have been made to produce a taxonomy of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_of_measurement" title=3D"Level of measureme=
nt">levels of measurement</a>. The psychophysicist <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Smith_Stevens" title=3D"Stanley Smith Stevens">Sta=
nley Smith Stevens</a> defined nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio scales=
. Nominal measurements do not have meaningful rank order among values, and =
permit any one-to-one (injective) transformation. Ordinal measurements have=
 imprecise differences between consecutive values, but have a meaningful or=
der to those values, and permit any order-preserving transformation. Interv=
al measurements have meaningful distances between measurements defined, but=
 the zero value is arbitrary (as in the case with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Longitude" title=3D"Longitude">longitude</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature" title=3D"Temperature">temperatu=
re</a> measurements in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celsius" ti=
tle=3D"Celsius">Celsius</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fah=
renheit" title=3D"Fahrenheit">Fahrenheit</a>), and permit any linear transf=
ormation. Ratio measurements have both a meaningful zero value and the dist=
ances between different measurements defined, and permit any rescaling tran=
sformation.
</p><p>Because variables conforming only to nominal or ordinal measurements=
 cannot be reasonably measured numerically, sometimes they are grouped toge=
ther as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_variable" titl=
e=3D"Categorical variable">categorical variables</a>, whereas ratio and int=
erval measurements are grouped together as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Variable_(mathematics)#Applied_statistics" title=3D"Variable (math=
ematics)">quantitative variables</a>, which can be either <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution#Discrete_probability_distr=
ibution" title=3D"Probability distribution">discrete</a> or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution#Continuous_probability_d=
istribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">continuous</a>, due to thei=
r numerical nature. Such distinctions can often be loosely correlated with =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_type" title=3D"Data type">dat=
a type</a> in computer science, in that dichotomous categorical variables m=
ay be represented with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean=
_data_type" title=3D"Boolean data type">Boolean data type</a>, polytomous c=
ategorical variables with arbitrarily assigned <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a> in the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_(computer_science)" title=3D"Integer (com=
puter science)">integral data type</a>, and continuous variables with the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_data_type" title=3D"Real data =
type">real data type</a> involving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Floating-point_arithmetic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating-po=
int arithmetic</a>. But the mapping of computer science data types to stati=
stical data types depends on which categorization of the latter is being im=
plemented.
</p><p>Other categorizations have been proposed. For example, Mosteller and=
 Tukey (1977)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> distinguished g=
rades, ranks, counted fractions, counts, amounts, and balances. Nelder (199=
0)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> described continuous count=
s, continuous ratios, count ratios, and categorical modes of data. (See als=
o: Chrisman (1998),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> van den B=
erg (1991).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>)
</p><p>The issue of whether or not it is appropriate to apply different kin=
ds of statistical methods to data obtained from different kinds of measurem=
ent procedures is complicated by issues concerning the transformation of va=
riables and the precise interpretation of research questions. "The relation=
ship between the data and what they describe merely reflects the fact that =
certain kinds of statistical statements may have truth values which are not=
 invariant under some transformations. Whether or not a transformation is s=
ensible to contemplate depends on the question one is trying to answer."<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap">=
<span title=3D"Page / location: 82">:=E2=80=8A82=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Methods">Methods</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Methods"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
