<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Descriptive_statistics">Des=
criptive statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Descriptive statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statisti=
cs" title=3D"Descriptive statistics">Descriptive statistics</a></div>
<p>A <b>descriptive statistic</b> (in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Count_noun" title=3D"Count noun">count noun</a> sense) is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summary_statistic" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Summary statistic">summary statistic</a> that quantitatively descr=
ibes or summarizes features of a collection of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Information" title=3D"Information">information</a>,<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tatistics#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> while <b>descriptive statistics</b> in=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_noun" title=3D"Mass noun=
">mass noun</a> sense is the process of using and analyzing those statistic=
s. Descriptive statistics is distinguished from <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistical_inference" title=3D"Statistical inference">infere=
ntial statistics</a> (or inductive statistics), in that descriptive statist=
ics aims to summarize a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_(st=
atistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample (statistics)">sample</a>, =
rather than use the data to learn about the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical population">populati=
on</a> that the sample of data is thought to represent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics=
#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inferential_statistics">Inf=
erential statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Inferential statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_inferenc=
e" title=3D"Statistical inference">Statistical inference</a></div>
<p><b>Statistical inference</b> is the process of using <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_analysis" title=3D"Data analysis">data analysis<=
/a> to deduce properties of an underlying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probab=
ility distribution</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Oxford_29-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Oxford-29"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Inferential statistical analysis infers properties of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statisti=
cal population">population</a>, for example by testing hypotheses and deriv=
ing estimates.  It is assumed that the observed data set is <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Sampling (statist=
ics)">sampled</a> from a larger population. Inferential statistics can be c=
ontrasted with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statist=
ics" title=3D"Descriptive statistics">descriptive statistics</a>. Descripti=
ve statistics is solely concerned with properties of the observed data, and=
 it does not rest on the assumption that the data come from a larger popula=
tion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Terminology_and_theory_of_i=
nferential_statistics">Terminology and theory of inferential statistics</h4=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</s=
pan><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Terminology and theo=
ry of inferential statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Statistics,_estimators_and_=
pivotal_quantities"><span id=3D"Statistics.2C_estimators_and_pivotal_quanti=
ties"></span>Statistics, estimators and pivotal quantities</h5><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Statistics, estimators and pivo=
tal quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Consider <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_identicall=
y_distributed" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent identically distr=
ibuted">independent identically distributed (IID) random variables</a> with=
 a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution"=
 title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a>: standard =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_inference" title=3D"St=
atistical inference">statistical inference</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Estimation_theory" title=3D"Estimation theory">estimation =
theory</a> defines a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_sample=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random sample">random sample</a> as the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Random vector">random vector</a> given by the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Column_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Column =
vector">column vector</a> of these IID variables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Piazza=
_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statist=
ics#cite_note-Piazza-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical population">population<=
/a> being examined is described by a probability distribution that may have=
 unknown parameters.
</p><p>A statistic is a random variable that is a function of the random sa=
mple, but <em>not a function of unknown parameters</em>. The probability di=
stribution of the statistic, though, may have unknown parameters. Consider =
now a function of the unknown parameter: an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Estimator" title=3D"Estimator">estimator</a> is a statistic used =
to estimate such function. Commonly used estimators include <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_mean" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sampl=
e mean">sample mean</a>, unbiased <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sample_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample variance">sample var=
iance</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_covariance" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample covariance">sample covariance</a>.
</p><p>A random variable that is a function of the random sample and of the=
 unknown parameter, but whose probability distribution <i>does not depend o=
n the unknown parameter</i> is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Pivotal_quantity" title=3D"Pivotal quantity">pivotal quantity</a> or =
pivot. Widely used pivots include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Z-score" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Z-score">z-score</a>, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution#Applications" =
title=3D"Chi-squared distribution">chi square statistic</a> and Student's <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution#How_the_=
t-distribution_arises" title=3D"Student's t-distribution">t-value</a>.
</p><p>Between two estimators of a given parameter, the one with lower <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error" title=3D"Mean squa=
red error">mean squared error</a> is said to be more <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient_estimator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Effi=
cient estimator">efficient</a>. Furthermore, an estimator is said to be <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unbiased_estimator" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Unbiased estimator">unbiased</a> if its <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expected value=
</a> is equal to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_value" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"True value">true value</a> of the unknown par=
ameter being estimated, and asymptotically unbiased if its expected value c=
onverges at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</a> to the true value of such parame=
ter.
</p><p>Other desirable properties for estimators include: <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UMVUE" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"UMVUE">UMVUE<=
/a> estimators that have the lowest variance for all possible values of the=
 parameter to be estimated (this is usually an easier property to verify th=
an efficiency) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistent_esti=
mator" title=3D"Consistent estimator">consistent estimators</a> which <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Converges_in_probability" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Converges in probability">converges in probability</a> to=
 the true value of such parameter.
</p><p>This still leaves the question of how to obtain estimators in a give=
n situation and carry the computation, several methods have been proposed: =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_moments_(statistics)=
" title=3D"Method of moments (statistics)">method of moments</a>, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_likelihood" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Maximum likelihood">maximum likelihood</a> method, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares" title=3D"Least squares">le=
ast squares</a> method and the more recent method of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimating_equations" title=3D"Estimating equations">est=
imating equations</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Null_hypothesis_and_alterna=
tive_hypothesis">Null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis</h5><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Null hypothesis and alternative=
 hypothesis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>Interpretation of statistical information can often involve the developm=
ent of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D=
"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> which is usually (but not necessarily=
) that no relationship exists among variables or that no change occurred ov=
er time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#=
cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alte=
rnative_hypothesis" title=3D"Alternative hypothesis">alternative hypothesis=
</a> is the name of the hypothesis that contradicts the null hypothesis.
</p><p>The best illustration for a novice is the predicament encountered by=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Criminal_trial" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Criminal trial">criminal trial</a>. The null hypothesis, H<=
sub>0</sub>, asserts that the defendant is innocent, whereas the alternativ=
e hypothesis, H<sub>1</sub>, asserts that the defendant is <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guilt_(law)" title=3D"Guilt (law)">guilty</a>. The=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indictment" title=3D"Indictment">=
indictment</a> comes because of suspicion of the guilt. The H<sub>0</sub> (=
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Status_quo" title=3D"Status qu=
o">status quo</a>) stands in opposition to H<sub>1</sub> and is maintained =
unless H<sub>1</sub> is supported by evidence "beyond a reasonable doubt". =
However, "failure to reject H<sub>0</sub>" in this case does not imply inno=
cence, but merely that the evidence was insufficient to convict. So the jur=
y does not necessarily <em>accept</em> H<sub>0</sub> but <em>fails to rejec=
t</em> H<sub>0</sub>. While one can not "prove" a null hypothesis, one can =
test how close it is to being true with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical power=
">power test</a>, which tests for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Type_II_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type II error">type II errors=
</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Error">Error</h5><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Error"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Working from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis"=
 title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a>, two broad categories of err=
or are recognized:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors#=
Type_I_error" title=3D"Type I and type II errors">Type I errors</a> where t=
he null hypothesis is falsely rejected, giving a "false positive".</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors#Type=
_II_error" title=3D"Type I and type II errors">Type II errors</a> where the=
 null hypothesis fails to be rejected and an actual difference between popu=
lations is missed, giving a "false negative".</li></ul>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"St=
andard deviation">Standard deviation</a> refers to the extent to which indi=
vidual observations in a sample differ from a central value, such as the sa=
mple or population mean, while <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sta=
ndard_error_(statistics)#Standard_error_of_the_mean" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Standard error (statistics)">Standard error</a> refers to an estim=
ate of difference between sample mean and population mean.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errors_and_residuals_in_s=
tatistics#Introduction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Errors and residuals=
 in statistics">statistical error</a> is the amount by which an observation=
 differs from its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_value" =
title=3D"Expected value">expected value</a>. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Errors_and_residuals_in_statistics#Introduction" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Errors and residuals in statistics">residual</a> is the a=
mount an observation differs from the value the estimator of the expected v=
alue assumes on a given sample (also called prediction).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error" title=
=3D"Mean squared error">Mean squared error</a> is used for obtaining <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient_estimators" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Efficient estimators">efficient estimators</a>, a widely used =
class of estimators. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_mean_squ=
are_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root mean square error">Root mean=
 square error</a> is simply the square root of mean squared error.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Linear_least_squares(2).svg" =
class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wiki=
pedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Linear_least_squares%282%29.svg/250px-Linear_least=
_squares%282%29.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"226" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"502" data-file-height=3D"454"></=
a><figcaption>A least squares fit: in red the points to be fitted, in blue =
the fitted line.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Many statistical methods seek to minimize the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Residual_sum_of_squares" title=3D"Residual sum of squares">r=
esidual sum of squares</a>, and these are called "<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares" title=3D"Least squares">methods of least squ=
ares</a>" in contrast to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_abs=
olute_deviations" title=3D"Least absolute deviations">Least absolute deviat=
ions</a>. The latter gives equal weight to small and big errors, while the =
former gives more weight to large errors. Residual sum of squares is also <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_function" title=3D"D=
ifferentiable function">differentiable</a>, which provides a handy property=
 for doing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" ti=
tle=3D"Regression analysis">regression</a>. Least squares applied to <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression" title=3D"Linear regre=
ssion">linear regression</a> is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=3D"Ordinary least squares">ordinary leas=
t squares</a> method and least squares applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_regression" title=3D"Nonlinear regression">nonlin=
ear regression</a> is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-l=
inear_least_squares" title=3D"Non-linear least squares">non-linear least sq=
uares</a>. Also in a linear regression model the non deterministic part of =
the model is called error term, disturbance or more simply noise. Both line=
ar regression and non-linear regression are addressed in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_least_squares" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Polynomial least squares">polynomial least squares</a>, which also des=
cribes the variance in a prediction of the dependent variable (y axis) as a=
 function of the independent variable (x axis) and the deviations (errors, =
noise, disturbances) from the estimated (fitted) curve.
</p><p>Measurement processes that generate statistical data are also subjec=
t to error.  Many of these errors are classified as <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Random_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random error=
">random</a> (noise) or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systematic=
_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Systematic error">systematic</a> (<a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias" title=3D"Bias">bias</a>), but =
other types of errors (e.g., blunder, such as when an analyst reports incor=
rect units) can also be important. The presence of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Missing_data" title=3D"Missing data">missing data</a> or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Censoring_(statistics)" title=3D"Ce=
nsoring (statistics)">censoring</a> may result in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bias_(statistics)" title=3D"Bias (statistics)">biased estim=
ates</a> and specific techniques have been developed to address these probl=
ems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Interval_estimation">Interv=
al estimation</h5><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: In=
terval estimation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_estimation"=
 title=3D"Interval estimation">Interval estimation</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NYW-confidence-interval.svg" =
class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wiki=
pedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/NYW-confidence-interval.svg/250px-NYW-confidence-i=
nterval.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"102" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"222" data-file-height=3D"91"></a><figcap=
tion><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_intervals" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confidence intervals">Confidence intervals</a>: t=
he red line is true value for the mean in this example, the blue lines are =
random confidence intervals for 100 realizations.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Most studies only sample part of a population, so results do not fully r=
epresent the whole population. Any estimates obtained from the sample only =
approximate the population value. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Confidence_intervals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confidence intervals">=
Confidence intervals</a> allow statisticians to express how closely the sam=
ple estimate matches the true value in the whole population. Often they are=
 expressed as 95% confidence intervals. Formally, a 95% confidence interval=
 for a value is a range where, if the sampling and analysis were repeated u=
nder the same conditions (yielding a different dataset), the interval would=
 include the true (population) value in 95% of all possible cases. This doe=
s <i>not</i> imply that the probability that the true value is in the confi=
dence interval is 95%. From the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fr=
equentist_inference" title=3D"Frequentist inference">frequentist</a> perspe=
ctive, such a claim does not even make sense, as the true value is not a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random var=
iable">random variable</a>.  Either the true value is or is not within the =
given interval. However, it is true that, before any data are sampled and g=
iven a plan for how to construct the confidence interval, the probability i=
s 95% that the yet-to-be-calculated interval will cover the true value: at =
this point, the limits of the interval are yet-to-be-observed <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">rand=
om variables</a>. One approach that does yield an interval that can be inte=
rpreted as having a given probability of containing the true value is to us=
e a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credible_interval" title=3D"Cr=
edible interval">credible interval</a> from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Bayesian_statistics" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian stati=
stics</a>: this approach depends on a different way of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_interpretations" title=3D"Probability inte=
rpretations">interpreting what is meant by "probability"</a>, that is as a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=3D"Bay=
esian probability">Bayesian probability</a>.
</p><p>In principle confidence intervals can be symmetrical or asymmetrical=
. An interval can be asymmetrical because it works as lower or upper bound =
for a parameter (left-sided interval or right sided interval), but it can a=
lso be asymmetrical because the two sided interval is built violating symme=
try around the estimate. Sometimes the bounds for a confidence interval are=
 reached asymptotically and these are used to approximate the true bounds.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Significance">Significance<=
/h5><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Significance"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_signific=
ance" title=3D"Statistical significance">Statistical significance</a></div>
<p>Statistics rarely give a simple Yes/No type answer to the question under=
 analysis. Interpretation often comes down to the level of statistical sign=
ificance applied to the numbers and often refers to the probability of a va=
lue accurately rejecting the null hypothesis (sometimes referred to as the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value" title=3D"P-value">p-value=
</a>).
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:P-value_in_statistical_signif=
icance_testing.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uploa=
d.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3a/P-value_in_statistical_signifi=
cance_testing.svg/500px-P-value_in_statistical_significance_testing.svg.png=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"450" height=3D"456" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"1224" data-file-height=3D"1239"></a><figcaption>In this=
 graph the black line is probability distribution for the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_statistic" title=3D"Test statistic">test stati=
stic</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Critical_region#Defi=
nition_of_terms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Critical region">critical r=
egion</a> is the set of values to the right of the observed data point (obs=
erved value of the test statistic) and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/P-value" title=3D"P-value">p-value</a> is represented by the green=
 area.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The standard approach<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Piazza_31-1" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Piazza-31">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> is to test a null hypothesis against an alternative hypothesis.=
 A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Critical_region#Definition_of_t=
erms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Critical region">critical region</a> i=
s the set of values of the estimator that leads to refuting the null hypoth=
esis. The probability of type I error is therefore the probability that the=
 estimator belongs to the critical region given that null hypothesis is tru=
e (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_significance" title=
=3D"Statistical significance">statistical significance</a>) and the probabi=
lity of type II error is the probability that the estimator does not belong=
 to the critical region given that the alternative hypothesis is true. The =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Statistical power">statistical power</a> of a test is the p=
robability that it correctly rejects the null hypothesis when the null hypo=
thesis is false.
</p><p>Referring to statistical significance does not necessarily mean that=
 the overall result is significant in real world terms. For example, in a l=
arge study of a drug it may be shown that the drug has a statistically sign=
ificant but very small beneficial effect, such that the drug is unlikely to=
 help the patient noticeably.
</p><p>Although in principle the acceptable level of statistical significan=
ce may be subject to debate, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
ignificance_level" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Significance level">signi=
ficance level</a> is the largest p-value that allows the test to reject the=
 null hypothesis. This test is logically equivalent to saying that the p-va=
lue is the probability, assuming the null hypothesis is true, of observing =
a result at least as extreme as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Test_statistic" title=3D"Test statistic">test statistic</a>. Therefore, t=
he smaller the significance level, the lower the probability of committing =
type I error.
</p><p>Some problems are usually associated with this framework (See <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing#Criticism=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">criticism =
of hypothesis testing</a>):
</p>
<ul><li>A difference that is highly statistically significant can still be =
of no practical significance, but it is possible to properly formulate test=
s to account for this. One response involves going beyond reporting only th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significance_level" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Significance level">significance level</a> to include th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value" title=3D"P-value"><i>p<=
/i>-value</a> when reporting whether a hypothesis is rejected or accepted. =
The p-value, however, does not indicate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Effect_size" title=3D"Effect size">size</a> or importance of the =
observed effect and can also seem to exaggerate the importance of minor dif=
ferences in large studies. A better and increasingly common approach is to =
report <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=
=3D"Confidence interval">confidence intervals</a>. Although these are produ=
ced from the same calculations as those of hypothesis tests or <i>p</i>-val=
ues, they describe both the size of the effect and the uncertainty surround=
ing it.</li>
<li>Fallacy of the transposed conditional, aka <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Prosecutor%27s_fallacy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prosecu=
tor's fallacy">prosecutor's fallacy</a>: criticisms arise because the hypot=
hesis testing approach forces one hypothesis (the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis<=
/a>) to be favored, since what is being evaluated is the probability of the=
 observed result given the null hypothesis and not probability of the null =
hypothesis given the observed result. An alternative to this approach is of=
fered by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=
=3D"Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference</a>, although it requires establ=
ishing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_probability" title=
=3D"Prior probability">prior probability</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ioannidis2=
005_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stat=
istics#cite_note-Ioannidis2005-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Rejecting the null hypothesis does not automatically prove the alternat=
ive hypothesis.</li>
<li>As everything in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferential_s=
tatistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inferential statistics">inferenti=
al statistics</a> it relies on sample size, and therefore under <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fat_tails" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fat=
 tails">fat tails</a> p-values may be seriously mis-computed.<sup class=3D"=
noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[=
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may nee=
d clarification or removal of jargon. (October 2016)">clarification needed<=
/span></a></i>]</sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h5><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some well-known statistical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sta=
tistical_hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hyp=
othesis testing">tests</a> and procedures are:
</p>
<div class=3D"div-col" style=3D"column-width: 22em;">
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance" titl=
e=3D"Analysis of variance">Analysis of variance</a> (ANOVA)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_test" title=3D"Chi=
-squared test">Chi-squared test</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation" title=3D"Correlat=
ion">Correlation</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor_analysis" title=3D"Fact=
or analysis">Factor analysis</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_(U)" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93Whitney (U)">Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <=
i>U</i></a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_square_weighted_deviation=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean square weighted deviation">Mean squar=
e weighted deviation</a> (MSWD)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_product-moment_correla=
tion_coefficient" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson product-moment cor=
relation coefficient">Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient</a></l=
i>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" title=3D"=
Regression analysis">Regression analysis</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_=
coefficient" title=3D"Spearman's rank correlation coefficient">Spearman's r=
ank correlation coefficient</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test" title=3D"S=
tudent's t-test">Student's <i>t</i>-test</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_series_analysis" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Time series analysis">Time series analysis</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjoint_Analysis" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Conjoint Analysis">Conjoint Analysis</a></li></ul></div=
>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bayesian_statistics">Bayesi=
an statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Ba=
yesian statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_statistics"=
 title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian statistics</a></div>
<p>An alternative paradigm to the popular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Frequentist_inference" title=3D"Frequentist inference">frequentist<=
/a> paradigm is to use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_th=
eorem" title=3D"Bayes' theorem">Bayes' theorem</a> to update the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_probability" title=3D"Prior probabilit=
y">prior probability</a> of the hypotheses in consideration based on the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood_function" title=3D"Likeli=
hood function">relative likelihood</a> of the evidence gathered to obtain a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"P=
osterior probability">posterior probability</a>. Bayesian methods have been=
 aided by the increase in available computing power to compute the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterior=
 probability">posterior probability</a> using numerical approximation techn=
iques like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_Chain_Monte_Carl=
o" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Markov Chain Monte Carlo">Markov Chain Mo=
nte Carlo</a>.
</p><p>For statistically modelling purposes, Bayesian models tend to be <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_hierarchical_modeling" title=
=3D"Bayesian hierarchical modeling">hierarchical</a>, for example, one coul=
d model each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YouTube" title=3D"You=
Tube">YouTube</a> channel as having video views distributed as a normal dis=
tribution with channel dependent mean and variance <span class=3D"mwe-math-=
element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-=
math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org=
/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\mathcal {N}}(\mu _{i},\sigma=
 _{i})}">
