-align: -0.838ex; margin-left: -0.062ex; width:9.508ex; height:3.009ex;" al=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\mathcal {N}}(\mu _{i},\sigma _{i})}"></span>, while m=
odeling the channel means as themselves coming from a normal distribution r=
epresenting the distribution of average video view counts per channel, and =
the variances as coming from another distribution.
</p><p>The concept of using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likeli=
hood_function#Likelihood_ratio" title=3D"Likelihood function">likelihood ra=
tio</a> can also be prominently seen in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Likelihood_ratios_in_diagnostic_testing" title=3D"Likelihood ratios i=
n diagnostic testing">medical diagnostic testing</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Exploratory_data_analysis">=
Exploratory data analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit =
section: Exploratory data analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploratory_data_ana=
lysis" title=3D"Exploratory data analysis">Exploratory data analysis</a></d=
iv>
<p><b>Exploratory data analysis</b> (<b>EDA</b>) is an approach to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_analysis" title=3D"Data analysis">an=
alyzing</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" title=3D"Dat=
a set">data sets</a> to summarize their main characteristics, often with vi=
sual methods. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model"=
 title=3D"Statistical model">statistical model</a> can be used or not, but =
primarily EDA is for seeing what the data can tell us beyond the formal mod=
eling or hypothesis testing task.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mathematical_statistics">Ma=
thematical statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Mathematical statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_statist=
ics" title=3D"Mathematical statistics">Mathematical statistics</a></div>
<p>Mathematical statistics is the application of mathematics to statistics.=
 Mathematical techniques used for this include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathema=
tical analysis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra=
" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Stochastic_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stochastic=
 analysis">stochastic analysis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Differential_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Differential equat=
ions">differential equations</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Measure-theoretic_probability_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Me=
asure-theoretic probability theory">measure-theoretic probability theory</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2=
_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statisti=
cs#cite_note-:2-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> All statistical analyses make use of at least=
 some mathematics, and mathematical statistics can therefore be regarded as=
 a fundamental component of general statistics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cit=
e_note-:3-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_statisti=
cs" title=3D"History of statistics">History of statistics</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Founders_of_statistics" title=3D"Founders=
 of statistics">Founders of statistics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jakob_Bernoulli.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19=
/Jakob_Bernoulli.jpg/250px-Jakob_Bernoulli.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"292" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2000" dat=
a-file-height=3D"2338"></a><figcaption>Bernoulli's <i><span title=3D"Latin-=
language text"><span lang=3D"la"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
rs_Conjectandi" title=3D"Ars Conjectandi">Ars Conjectandi</a></span></span>=
</i> was the first work that dealt with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</=
a> as currently understood.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Formal discussions on inference date back to the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Mathematics in medieval Islam">mathematicians</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cry=
ptographers">cryptographers</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" title=3D"Islamic Golden Age">Islamic Golden Age</a=
> between the 8th and 13th centuries. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Al-Khalil_ibn_Ahmad_al-Farahidi" title=3D"Al-Khalil ibn Ahmad al-Farahi=
di">Al-Khalil</a> (717=E2=80=93786) wrote the <i>Book of Cryptographic Mess=
ages</i>, which contains one of the first uses of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"Permutation">permutations</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combination" title=3D"Combination">co=
mbinations</a>, to list all possible Arabic words with and without vowels.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-LB_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-LB-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Kindi" title=3D"Al-Kindi">Al-Kindi</a>'s <i>Manuscri=
pt on Deciphering Cryptographic Messages</i> gave a detailed description of=
 how to use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency_analysis" ti=
tle=3D"Frequency analysis">frequency analysis</a> to decipher <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encrypted" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Encry=
pted">encrypted</a> messages, providing an early example of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_inference" title=3D"Statistical infer=
ence">statistical inference</a> for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Code" title=3D"Code">decoding</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ibn_Adlan" title=3D"Ibn Adlan">Ibn Adlan</a> (1187=E2=80=931268) later m=
ade an important contribution on the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sample_size" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample size">sample s=
ize</a> in frequency analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LB_36-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-LB-36"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>Although the term <i>statistic</i> was introduced by the Italian sch=
olar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girolamo_Ghilini" title=3D"Gi=
rolamo Ghilini">Girolamo Ghilini</a> in 1589 with reference to a collection=
 of facts and information about a state, it was the German <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Achenwall" title=3D"Gottfried Achenwall"=
>Gottfried Achenwall</a> in 1749 who started using the term as a collection=
 of quantitative information, in the modern use for this science.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistics#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-38"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The earliest writing containing statistics in Europe dates back to =
1663, with the publication of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
atural_and_Political_Observations_upon_the_Bills_of_Mortality" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Natural and Political Observations upon the Bills of Mor=
tality">Natural and Political Observations upon the Bills of Mortality</a><=
/i> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Graunt" title=3D"John =
Graunt">John Graunt</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Earl=
y applications of statistical thinking revolved around the needs of states =
to base policy on demographic and economic data, hence its <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_statistics#Etymology" title=3D"History =
of statistics"><i>stat-</i> etymology</a>. The scope of the discipline of s=
tatistics broadened in the early 19th century to include the collection and=
 analysis of data in general. Today, statistics is widely employed in gover=
nment, business, and natural and social sciences.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_J=
ensen.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimed=
ia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_Jensen.jpg=
/250px-Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_Jensen.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"318" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1639" dat=
a-file-height=3D"2088"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Ga=
uss</a> made major contributions to probabilistic methods leading to statis=
tics.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The mathematical foundations of statistics developed from discussions co=
ncerning <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_of_chance" title=3D"=
Game of chance">games of chance</a> among mathematicians such as <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Cardano"=
>Gerolamo Cardano</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_Pasc=
al" title=3D"Blaise Pascal">Blaise Pascal</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat<=
/a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title=
=3D"Christiaan Huygens">Christiaan Huygens</a>. Although the idea of probab=
ility was already examined in ancient and medieval law and philosophy (such=
 as the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Caramuel" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Juan Caramuel">Juan Caramuel</a>), <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability theor=
y">probability theory</a> as a mathematical discipline only took shape at t=
he very end of the 17th century, particularly in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Bernoulli" title=3D"Jacob Bernoulli">Jacob Bernoulli</=
a>'s posthumous work <i><span title=3D"Latin-language text"><span lang=3D"l=
a"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ars_Conjectandi" title=3D"Ars C=
onjectandi">Ars Conjectandi</a></span></span></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite=
_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> This was the first book where the realm of games of c=
hance and the realm of the probable (which concerned opinion, evidence, and=
 argument) were combined and submitted to mathematical analysis.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tatistics#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Method_of_least_squares" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Method of le=
ast squares">method of least squares</a> was first described by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrien-Marie_Legendre" title=3D"Adrien-Marie =
Legendre">Adrien-Marie Legendre</a> in 1805, though <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl=
 Friedrich Gauss</a> presumably made use of it a decade earlier in 1795.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Karl_Pearson,_1910.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/1/18/Karl_Pearson%2C_1910.jpg/250px-Karl_Pearson%2C_1910.jpg=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"182" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"1177" data-file-height=3D"856"></a><figcaption><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl=
 Pearson</a>, a founder of mathematical statistics</figcaption></figure>
<p>The modern field of statistics emerged in the late 19th and early 20th c=
entury in three stages.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
first wave, at the turn of the century, was led by the work of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Galton" title=3D"Francis Galton">Franc=
is Galton</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" ti=
tle=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>, who transformed statistics into a ri=
gorous mathematical discipline used for analysis, not just in science, but =
in industry and politics as well. Galton's contributions included introduci=
ng the concepts of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviat=
ion" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation" title=3D"Correlation">correlation</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" title=3D"Reg=
ression analysis">regression analysis</a> and the application of these meth=
ods to the study of the variety of human characteristics=E2=80=94height, we=
ight and eyelash length among others.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Galton1877_44-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite=
_note-Galton1877-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Pearson developed the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_product-moment_correlation_coefficient" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient">P=
earson product-moment correlation coefficient</a>, defined as a product-mom=
ent,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_moments_(statistics)" title=3D"Method of mom=
ents (statistics)">method of moments</a> for the fitting of distributions t=
o samples and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_distribu=
tion" title=3D"Pearson distribution">Pearson distribution</a>, among many o=
ther things.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pearson,_On_the_criterion_46-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Pear=
son,_On_the_criterion-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Galton and Pearson founded <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biometrika" title=3D"Biometrika">Biometri=
ka</a></i> as the first journal of mathematical statistics and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biostatistics" title=3D"Biostatistics">biostat=
istics</a> (then called <i>biometry</i>), and the latter founded the world'=
s first university statistics department at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/University_College_London" title=3D"University College London">Un=
iversity College London</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-47"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The second wave of the 1910s and 20s was initiated by <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Sealy_Gosset" title=3D"William Sealy Gos=
set">William Sealy Gosset</a>, and reached its culmination in the insights =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Fisher" title=3D"Ronald =
Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a>, who wrote the textbooks that were to define the =
academic discipline in universities around the world. Fisher's most importa=
nt publications were his 1918 seminal paper <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/The_Correlation_between_Relatives_on_the_Supposition_of_Mendel=
ian_Inheritance" title=3D"The Correlation between Relatives on the Supposit=
ion of Mendelian Inheritance">The Correlation between Relatives on the Supp=
osition of Mendelian Inheritance</a></i> (which was the first to use the st=
atistical term, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D=
"Variance">variance</a>), his classic 1925 work <i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_Methods_for_Research_Workers" title=3D"Statist=
ical Methods for Research Workers">Statistical Methods for Research Workers=
</a></i> and his 1935 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Desig=
n_of_Experiments" title=3D"The Design of Experiments">The Design of Experim=
ents</a></i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tics#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-50"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> where he developed rigorous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desi=
gn_of_experiments" title=3D"Design of experiments">design of experiments</a=
> models. He originated the concepts of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sufficiency_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sufficiency =
(statistics)">sufficiency</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anc=
illary_statistic" title=3D"Ancillary statistic">ancillary statistics</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_discriminant_analysis" title=
=3D"Linear discriminant analysis">Fisher's linear discriminator</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher_information" title=3D"Fisher i=
nformation">Fisher information</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-51"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> He also coined the term <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nul=
l_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> during the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lady_tasting_tea" title=3D"Lady tastin=
g tea">Lady tasting tea</a> experiment, which "is never proved or establish=
ed, but is possibly disproved, in the course of experimentation".<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-oed_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-oed-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_not=
e-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> In his 1930 book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/The_Genetical_Theory_of_Natural_Selection" title=3D"The Genetical Theor=
y of Natural Selection">The Genetical Theory of Natural Selection</a></i>, =
he applied statistics to various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
iology" title=3D"Biology">biological</a> concepts such as <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%27s_principle" title=3D"Fisher's principle">=
Fisher's principle</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Edwards98_54-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Edwards98-=
54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> (which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._W._F._Ed=
wards" title=3D"A. W. F. Edwards">A. W. F. Edwards</a> called "probably the=
 most celebrated argument in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolu=
tionary_biology" title=3D"Evolutionary biology">evolutionary biology</a>") =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisherian_runaway" title=3D"Fi=
sherian runaway">Fisherian runaway</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fisher15_55-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite=
_note-fisher15-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-fisher30_56-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-fis=
her30-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-pers00_57-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-pers00-57"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-ander94_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-ander94-58"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-ander06_59-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-ander06-59"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-gayon10_60-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-gayon10-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a concept in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexual_selection" title=3D"Sexual selection">=
sexual selection</a> about a positive feedback runaway effect found in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution" title=3D"Evolution">evoluti=
on</a>.
</p><p>The final wave, which mainly saw the refinement and expansion of ear=
lier developments, emerged from the collaborative work between <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egon_Pearson" title=3D"Egon Pearson">Egon Pear=
son</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerzy_Neyman" title=3D=
"Jerzy Neyman">Jerzy Neyman</a> in the 1930s. They introduced the concepts =
of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors" tit=
le=3D"Type I and type II errors">Type II</a>" error, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_a_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Power of=
 a test">power of a test</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onfidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence intervals</a>.=
 Jerzy Neyman in 1934 showed that stratified random sampling was in general=
 a better method of estimation than purposive (quota) sampling.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St=
atistics#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Among the early attempts to measure national economic activity were =
those of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Petty" title=3D"W=
illiam Petty">William Petty</a> in the 17th century. In the 20th century th=
e uniform <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_National_Accou=
nts" title=3D"System of National Accounts">System of National Accounts</a> =
was developed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Today, statistical methods are applied in all fields that involve de=
cision making, for making accurate inferences from a collated body of data =
and for making decisions in the face of uncertainty based on statistical me=
thodology. The use of modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compu=
ter" title=3D"Computer">computers</a> has expedited large-scale statistical=
 computations and has also made possible new methods that are impractical t=
o perform manually. Statistics continues to be an area of active research, =
for example on the problem of how to analyze <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Big_data" title=3D"Big data">big data</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#c=
ite_note-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Applied_statistics,_theoret=
ical_statistics_and_mathematical_statistics"><span id=3D"Applied_statistics=
.2C_theoretical_statistics_and_mathematical_statistics"></span>Applied stat=
istics, theoretical statistics and mathematical statistics</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Applied statistics, theoretical=
 statistics and mathematical statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Applied statistics,</i> sometimes referred to as <i>Statistical scien=
ce,</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> comprises descriptive=
 statistics and the application of inferential statistics.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statist=
ics#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-66"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 <i>Theoretical statistics</i> concerns the logical arguments underlying ju=
stification of approaches to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati=
stical_inference" title=3D"Statistical inference">statistical inference</a>=
, as well as encompassing <i>mathematical statistics</i>. Mathematical stat=
istics includes not only the manipulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">pro=
bability distributions</a> necessary for deriving results related to method=
s of estimation and inference, but also various aspects of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_statistics" title=3D"Computational s=
tatistics">computational statistics</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Design_of_experiments" title=3D"Design of experiments">design=
 of experiments</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_consultant" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical consultant">Statistical consultants=
</a> can help organizations and companies that do not have in-house experti=
se relevant to their particular questions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Machine_learning_and_data_m=
ining">Machine learning and data mining</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" =
title=3D"Edit section: Machine learning and data mining"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Mach=
ine learning">Machine learning</a> models are statistical and probabilistic=
 models that capture patterns in the data through use of computational algo=
rithms.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Statistics_in_academia">Sta=
tistics in academia</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Statistics in academia"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Statistics is applicable to a wide variety of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Academic_discipline" title=3D"Academic discipline">academic =
disciplines</a>, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural=
_science" title=3D"Natural science">natural</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Social_science" title=3D"Social science">social sciences<=
/a>, government, and business. Business statistics applies statistical meth=
ods in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econometrics" title=3D"Econ=
ometrics">econometrics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditi=
ng" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Auditing">auditing</a> and production an=
d operations, including services improvement and marketing research.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Statistics#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A study of two journals in tropical=
 biology found that the 12 most frequent statistical tests are: <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance" title=3D"Analysis of va=
riance">analysis of variance</a> (ANOVA), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Chi-squared_test" title=3D"Chi-squared test">chi-squared test</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test" title=3D"Stude=
nt's t-test">Student's t-test</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Linear_regression" title=3D"Linear regression">linear regression</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson%27s_correlation_coefficient" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson's correlation coefficient">Pearson's =
correlation coefficient</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann-=
Whitney_U_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mann-Whitney U test">Mann-Wh=
itney U test</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal-Wallis_t=
est" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kruskal-Wallis test">Kruskal-Wallis tes=
t</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diversity_index#Shannon_ind=
ex" title=3D"Diversity index">Shannon's diversity index</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tukey%27s_range_test" title=3D"Tukey's range tes=
t">Tukey's range test</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster=
_analysis" title=3D"Cluster analysis">cluster analysis</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient" title=
=3D"Spearman's rank correlation coefficient">Spearman's rank correlation co=
efficient</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compon=
ent_analysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">principal component an=
alysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_68-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-:0-68"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A typical statistics course covers descriptive statistics, probabili=
ty, binomial and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distributi=
on" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distributions</a>, test of hypothe=
ses and confidence intervals, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line=
ar_regression" title=3D"Linear regression">linear regression</a>, and corre=
lation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Modern fundamental st=
atistical courses for undergraduate students focus on correct test selectio=
n, results interpretation, and use of free statistics software.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-:0_68-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Statistics#cite_note-:0-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Statistical_computing">Stat=
istical computing</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Statistical computing"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_statis=
tics" title=3D"Computational statistics">Computational statistics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gretl_screenshot.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/b/b9/Gretl_screenshot.png/330px-Gretl_screenshot.png" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"290" height=3D"247" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"990" data-file-height=3D"844"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gretl" title=3D"Gretl">gretl</a>, an example of an =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_open_source_statistical_pa=
ckages" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"List of open source statistical pack=
ages">open source statistical package</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The rapid and sustained increases in computing power starting from the s=
econd half of the 20th century have had a substantial impact on the practic=
e of statistical science. Early statistical models were almost always from =
the class of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_model" title=
=3D"Linear model">linear models</a>, but powerful computers, coupled with s=
uitable numerical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithms" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algorithms">algorithms</a>, caused an increased =
interest in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_regression" =
title=3D"Nonlinear regression">nonlinear models</a> (such as <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Artificial neural network">neural networks</a>) as well as the cr=
eation of new types, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gener=
alized_linear_model" title=3D"Generalized linear model">generalized linear =
models</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilevel_model" t=
itle=3D"Multilevel model">multilevel models</a>.
</p><p>Increased computing power has also led to the growing popularity of =
computationally intensive methods based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Resampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Resampling (statistics)">resampl=
ing</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_test"=
 title=3D"Permutation test">permutation tests</a> and the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bootstrapping_(statistics)" title=3D"Bootstrapping =
(statistics)">bootstrap</a>, while techniques such as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibbs_sampling" title=3D"Gibbs sampling">Gibbs sampling=
</a> have made use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_mod=
el" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bayesian model">Bayesian models</a> more=
 feasible. The computer revolution has implications for the future of stati=
stics with a new emphasis on "experimental" and "empirical" statistics. A l=
arge number of both general and special purpose <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/List_of_statistical_packages" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
List of statistical packages">statistical software</a> are now available. E=
xamples of available software capable of complex statistical computation in=
clude programs such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematica=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematica">Mathematica</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SAS_(software)" title=3D"SAS (software)">SAS</=
a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SPSS" title=3D"SPSS">SPSS</a>,=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_(programming_language)" tit=
le=3D"R (programming language)">R</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Business_statistics">Busine=
ss statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Bu=
siness statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_mathematics#Uni=
versity_level" title=3D"Business mathematics">Business mathematics =C2=A7&n=
bsp;University level</a></div>
<p>In business, "statistics" is a widely used <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Management#Nature_of_work" title=3D"Management">management-</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_support" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Decision support">decision support</a> tool. It is part=
icularly applied in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_mana=
gement" title=3D"Financial management">financial management</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marketing_management" title=3D"Marketing man=
agement">marketing management</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Manufacturing_process_management" title=3D"Manufacturing process manag=
ement">production</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operations_=
management_for_services" title=3D"Operations management for services">servi=
ces</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operations_management"=
 title=3D"Operations management">operations management</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tics#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-71"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Statistics is also heavily used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Management_accounting" title=3D"Management accounting">management accoun=
ting</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditing" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Auditing">auditing</a>. The discipline of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Management_Science" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Management Science">Management Science</a> formalizes the use of statis=
tics, and other mathematics, in business. (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Econometrics" title=3D"Econometrics">Econometrics</a> is the appli=
cation of statistical methods to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
conomic_data" title=3D"Economic data">economic data</a> in order to give em=
pirical content to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_theory=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Economic theory">economic relationships</a=
>.)
</p><p>A typical "Business Statistics" course is intended for <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_education#Undergraduate_education" tit=
le=3D"Business education">business majors</a>, and covers<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statisti=
cs#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descr=
iptive_statistics" title=3D"Descriptive statistics">descriptive statistics<=
/a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_collection" title=3D"Dat=
a collection">collection</a>, description, analysis, and summary of data), =
probability (typically the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomia=
l_distribution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distrib=
ution">normal distributions</a>), test of hypotheses and confidence interva=
ls, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression" title=3D"Li=
near regression">linear regression</a>, and correlation; (follow-on) course=
s may include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting" title=
=3D"Forecasting">forecasting</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Time_series" title=3D"Time series">time series</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_trees" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decision t=
rees">decision trees</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple=
_linear_regression" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multiple linear regressi=
on">multiple linear regression</a>, and other topics from <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_analytics" title=3D"Business analytics">bu=
siness analytics</a> more generally. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Professional_certification_in_financial_services" title=3D"Professional =
certification in financial services">Professional certification programs</a=
>, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chartered_Financial=
_Analyst" title=3D"Chartered Financial Analyst">CFA</a>, often include topi=
cs in statistics.
</p>
