</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Misuse">Misuse</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Misuse"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misuse_of_statistics=
" title=3D"Misuse of statistics">Misuse of statistics</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misuse_of_statistics" title=3D"=
Misuse of statistics">Misuse of statistics</a> can produce subtle but serio=
us errors in description and interpretation=E2=80=94subtle in the sense tha=
t even experienced professionals make such errors, and serious in the sense=
 that they can lead to devastating decision errors. For instance, social po=
licy, medical practice, and the reliability of structures like bridges all =
rely on the proper use of statistics.
</p><p>Even when statistical techniques are correctly applied, the results =
can be difficult to interpret for those lacking expertise. The <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_significance" title=3D"Statistical=
 significance">statistical significance</a> of a trend in the data=E2=80=94=
which measures the extent to which a trend could be caused by random variat=
ion in the sample=E2=80=94may or may not agree with an intuitive sense of i=
ts significance. The set of basic statistical skills (and skepticism) that =
people need to deal with information in their everyday lives properly is re=
ferred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_literacy"=
 title=3D"Statistical literacy">statistical literacy</a>.
</p><p>There is a general perception that statistical knowledge is all-too-=
frequently intentionally <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misuse_of=
_statistics" title=3D"Misuse of statistics">misused</a> by finding ways to =
interpret only the data that are favorable to the presenter.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Huff_73-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Statistics#cite_note-Huff-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A mistrust and misunderstanding=
 of statistics is associated with the quotation, "<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Lies,_damned_lies,_and_statistics" title=3D"Lies, damned li=
es, and statistics">There are three kinds of lies: lies, damned lies, and s=
tatistics</a>". Misuse of statistics can be both inadvertent and intentiona=
l, and the book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/How_to_Lie_with=
_Statistics" title=3D"How to Lie with Statistics">How to Lie with Statistic=
s</a></i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Huff_73-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Huff-73"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> by <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darrell_Huff" title=3D"Darrell Huff">=
Darrell Huff</a>, outlines a range of considerations. In an attempt to shed=
 light on the use and misuse of statistics, reviews of statistical techniqu=
es used in particular fields are conducted (e.g. Warne, Lazo, Ramos, and Ri=
tter (2012)).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Ways to avoid misuse of statistics include using proper diagrams and=
 avoiding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias_(statistics)" title=
=3D"Bias (statistics)">bias</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Statistics_in_Archaeolo=
gy_75-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati=
stics#cite_note-Statistics_in_Archaeology-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Misuse can occur =
when conclusions are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hasty_general=
ization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hasty generalization">overgeneraliz=
ed</a> and claimed to be representative of more than they really are, often=
 by either deliberately or unconsciously overlooking sampling bias.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Misuse_of_Statistics_76-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Misuse_of_Statistics-76"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Bar graphs are arguably the easiest diagrams to use and understand=
, and they can be made either by hand or with simple computer programs.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Statistics_in_Archaeology_75-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Statistics_in_Archae=
ology-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Most people do not look for bias or errors, so they a=
re not noticed. Thus, people may often believe that something is true even =
if it is not well <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statis=
tics)" title=3D"Sampling (statistics)">represented</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Misuse_of_Statistics_76-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-Misuse_of_Statistics-76"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To m=
ake data gathered from statistics believable and accurate, the sample taken=
 must be representative of the whole.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Modern_Elementary_=
Statistics_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Statistics#cite_note-Modern_Elementary_Statistics-77"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Accord=
ing to Huff, "The dependability of a sample can be destroyed by [bias]... a=
llow yourself some degree of skepticism."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_note-78"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>To assist in the understanding of statistics Huff proposed a series =
of questions to be asked in each case:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Huff_73-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics#cite_not=
e-Huff-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Who says so? (Do they have an axe to grind?)</li>
<li>How do they know? (Do they have the resources to know the facts?)</li>
<li>What's missing? (Do they give us a complete picture?)</li>
<li>Did someone change the subject? (Do they offer us the right answer to t=
he wrong problem?)</li>
<li>Does it make sense? (Is their conclusion logical and consistent with wh=
at we already know?)</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Misinterpretation:_correlat=
ion">Misinterpretation: correlation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DStatistics&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Misinterpretation: correlation"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_does_not_imp=
ly_causation" title=3D"Correlation does not imply causation">Correlation do=
es not imply causation</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Simple_Confounding_Case.svg" =
class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wiki=
pedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Simple_Confounding_Case.svg/250px-Simple_Confoundi=
ng_Case.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"230" height=3D"213" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"152" data-file-height=3D"141"></a><figca=
ption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confounding_variable" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confounding variable">confounding variable</a>=
 problem: <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> may be correlated, not because there is cau=
sal relationship between them, but because both depend on a third variable =
<i>Z</i>. <i>Z</i> is called a confounding factor.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation" tit=
le=3D"Correlation">correlation</a> is particularly noteworthy for the poten=
tial confusion it can cause. Statistical analysis of a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" title=3D"Data set">data set</a> often reveal=
s that two variables (properties) of the population under consideration ten=
d to vary together, as if they were connected. For example, a study of annu=
al income that also looks at age of death, might find that poor people tend=
 to have shorter lives than affluent people. The two variables are said to =
be correlated; however, they may or may not be the cause of one another. Th=
e correlation phenomena could be caused by a third, previously unconsidered=
 phenomenon, called a lurking variable or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Confounding_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confounding va=
riable">confounding variable</a>. For this reason, there is no way to immed=
iately infer the existence of a causal relationship between the two variabl=
es.
</p>
